{"parentUuid":null,"isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a426968626a78bc3d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"You are a web research agent. Use WebSearch and WebFetch tools (load them first via ToolSearch with query \"select:WebSearch,WebFetch\"). Research this angle and return findings with cited URLs.\n\nANGLE: Memorization vs. generalization in memory/agent benchmarks. How do LoCoMo, LongMemEval, Letta memory benchmarks, and Mem0 avoid measuring trivial answer-lookup / recall? What corpus-design rules make a memory benchmark test TRANSFER (a stored lesson helps on NEW but related tasks) rather than recall of a stored answer? Look for: train/test separation by task vs by answer, held-out variants, paraphrase/transfer splits, multi-hop vs single-hop questions, \"answer leakage\" critiques of these benchmarks.\n\nSearch queries to try: \"LongMemEval benchmark abstention reasoning\", \"LoCoMo benchmark criticism multi-hop\", \"Mem0 benchmark methodology answer lookup\", \"Letta memory benchmark generalization\", \"memory benchmark answer leakage contamination\", \"agent benchmark transfer vs memorization held-out\".\n\nDo 6-10 searches, fetch the 6-8 most relevant pages (arxiv papers, blog posts from Letta/Mem0, benchmark repos). Extract concrete, falsifiable claims. Return a list of findings each with: the claim, the source URL, and a one-line note on reliability. Be concrete about corpus-design rules. Return findings only as your final message."},"uuid":"d72f8aee-d313-4956-9f1c-65431565ad9a","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:13:38.163Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
