{"parentUuid":"9702cee6-a645-40b3-8b7e-c52d053fabc3","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a426968626a78bc3d","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_015zN65P2s3gPoJfTs5zYXXt","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_0141VYwNKE6rgsTFzUAx6Hm3","name":"WebSearch","input":{"query":"Letta memory benchmark generalization evaluation"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1003,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5883,"cache_read_input_tokens":6421,"output_tokens":296,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5883},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1003,"output_tokens":296,"cache_read_input_tokens":6421,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5883,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5883,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":{"cache_miss_reason":{"type":"tools_changed","cache_missed_input_tokens":8234}}},"requestId":"req_011CcFqJ5yDkcuGwP5xwiQDL","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"199c7afe-8b76-47a6-a5c2-51bf7006d2a1","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:13:44.802Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"7b7d66ba-1a41-4ef9-bbc3-b84387d6195d","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a426968626a78bc3d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NtJjduAL8rtUx8UUwJLodc","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"LongMemEval benchmark abstention reasoning answer leakage\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"LongMemEval Benchmark\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/longmemeval-benchmark\"},{\"title\":\"agentmemory/benchmark/LONGMEMEVAL.md at main · rohitg00/agentmemory\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/rohitg00/agentmemory/blob/main/benchmark/LONGMEMEVAL.md\"},{\"title\":\"LongMemEval: LLM Long-Term Memory Benchmark\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/longmemeval\"},{\"title\":\"LongMemEval: Benchmarking Chat Assist- ants on Long-Term Interactive Memory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v2\"},{\"title\":\"[2410.10813] LongMemEval: Benchmarking Chat Assistants on Long-Term Interactive Memory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.10813\"},{\"title\":\"longmemeval: benchmarking chat assist\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2410.10813\"},{\"title\":\"LongMemEval\",\"url\":\"https://xiaowu0162.github.io/long-mem-eval/\"},{\"title\":\"LongMemEval-V2: Evaluating Long-Term Agent Memory Toward Experienced Colleagues\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2605.12493v1\"},{\"title\":\"SGMem: Sentence Graph Memory for Long-Term Conversational Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.21212\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about LongMemEval and the specific aspects you asked about:\n\n## LongMemEval Benchmark Overview\n\nLongMemEval is a comprehensive and challenging benchmark designed to evaluate the long-term memory abilities of chat assistants across five core memory tasks: information extraction, multi-session reasoning, temporal reasoning, knowledge updates, and abstention.\n\n## Abstention in LongMemEval\n\nAbstention (ABS) is the ability to decline to answer when information was never mentioned in the history (false premises). Abstention involves recognizing unanswerable queries and refraining from hallucination—critical for reliability.\n\n## Dataset Composition and Question Types\n\nWith 500 meticulously curated questions embedded within freely scalable user-assistant chat histories, LongMemEval presents a significant challenge to existing long-term memory systems, with commercial chat assistants and long-context LLMs showing a 30% accuracy drop on memorizing information across sustained interactions.\n\n## Abstention and Answer Leakage Concerns\n\nThe search results reference abstention questions that are intentionally constructed with misleading premises and do not primarily test ordinary evidence use. Additionally, pilot studies were conducted to understand whether the benchmark questions can be answered without trajectory evidence and whether oracle access to answer-bearing trajectories is sufficient for reliable question answering.\n\nThese pilot studies appear designed to detect potential answer leakage issues where models might answer questions without proper evidence from the conversation history.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"a72a2ea8-cf10-4310-a0ee-3dabf6073682","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:13:52.544Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"LongMemEval benchmark abstention reasoning answer leakage","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01LTF855iDH1nHZKmQpzjzow","content":[{"title":"LongMemEval Benchmark","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/longmemeval-benchmark"},{"title":"agentmemory/benchmark/LONGMEMEVAL.md at main · rohitg00/agentmemory","url":"https://github.com/rohitg00/agentmemory/blob/main/benchmark/LONGMEMEVAL.md"},{"title":"LongMemEval: LLM Long-Term Memory Benchmark","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/longmemeval"},{"title":"LongMemEval: Benchmarking Chat Assist- ants on Long-Term Interactive Memory","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v2"},{"title":"[2410.10813] LongMemEval: Benchmarking Chat Assistants on Long-Term Interactive Memory","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.10813"},{"title":"longmemeval: benchmarking chat assist","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2410.10813"},{"title":"LongMemEval","url":"https://xiaowu0162.github.io/long-mem-eval/"},{"title":"LongMemEval-V2: Evaluating Long-Term Agent Memory Toward Experienced Colleagues","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2605.12493v1"},{"title":"SGMem: Sentence Graph Memory for Long-Term Conversational Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.21212"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about LongMemEval and the specific aspects you asked about:\n\n## LongMemEval Benchmark Overview\n\nLongMemEval is a comprehensive and challenging benchmark designed to evaluate the long-term memory abilities of chat assistants across five core memory tasks: information extraction, multi-session reasoning, temporal reasoning, knowledge updates, and abstention.\n\n## Abstention in LongMemEval\n\nAbstention (ABS) is the ability to decline to answer when information was never mentioned in the history (false premises). Abstention involves recognizing unanswerable queries and refraining from hallucination—critical for reliability.\n\n## Dataset Composition and Question Types\n\nWith 500 meticulously curated questions embedded within freely scalable user-assistant chat histories, LongMemEval presents a significant challenge to existing long-term memory systems, with commercial chat assistants and long-context LLMs showing a 30% accuracy drop on memorizing information across sustained interactions.\n\n## Abstention and Answer Leakage Concerns\n\nThe search results reference abstention questions that are intentionally constructed with misleading premises and do not primarily test ordinary evidence use. Additionally, pilot studies were conducted to understand whether the benchmark questions can be answered without trajectory evidence and whether oracle access to answer-bearing trajectories is sufficient for reliable question answering.\n\nThese pilot studies appear designed to detect potential answer leakage issues where models might answer questions without proper evidence from the conversation history."],"durationSeconds":8.991725459000095,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"7b7d66ba-1a41-4ef9-bbc3-b84387d6195d","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"199c7afe-8b76-47a6-a5c2-51bf7006d2a1","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a426968626a78bc3d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0141VYwNKE6rgsTFzUAx6Hm3","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Letta memory benchmark generalization evaluation\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Benchmarking AI Agent Memory: Is a Filesystem All You Need? | Letta\",\"url\":\"https://www.letta.com/blog/benchmarking-ai-agent-memory/\"},{\"title\":\"Feature Request: Add Standard Memory Evaluation Benchmarks (LOCOMO, MemBench, LongMemEval) · Issue #3115 · letta-ai/letta\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/letta-ai/letta/issues/3115\"},{\"title\":\"Letta Leaderboard: Benchmarking LLMs on Agentic Memory | Letta\",\"url\":\"https://www.letta.com/blog/letta-leaderboard\"},{\"title\":\"Letta\",\"url\":\"https://www.letta.com/blog-categories/research\"},{\"title\":\"Mem0 vs Letta (MemGPT): AI Agent Memory Compared (2026)\",\"url\":\"https://vectorize.io/articles/mem0-vs-letta\"},{\"title\":\"The First Controlled Benchmark of AI Memory in Coding Agents | by Markus Sandelin | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@mrsandelin/the-first-controlled-benchmark-of-ai-memory-in-coding-agents-8e0bb776d39e\"},{\"title\":\"5 AI Agent Memory Systems Compared: Mem0, Zep, Letta, Supermemory, SuperLocalMemory (2026 Benchmark Data) - DEV Community\",\"url\":\"https://dev.to/varun_pratapbhardwaj_b13/5-ai-agent-memory-systems-compared-mem0-zep-letta-supermemory-superlocalmemory-2026-benchmark-59p3\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about Letta memory benchmark and generalization evaluation:\n\n## Letta Memory Benchmark Overview\n\nThe Letta Memory Benchmark (Letta Leaderboard) provides an apples-to-apples comparison evaluating different models' capabilities in terms of memory management, keeping the framework and tools constant. The Letta Leaderboard is a comprehensive benchmark suite that evaluates how effectively LLMs manage agentic memory.\n\n## Benchmark Components\n\nThe archival memory read benchmark measures how well models understand when to query for information beyond the information in their immediate context. To evaluate the agent's ability to retrieve missing information about the current topic, the benchmark stores all relevant facts in the archival memory, which is hidden from the agent unless it uses the archival memory search method, ensuring the agent has no prior knowledge and must rely on archival memory to answer correctly.\n\n## Generalization Limitations\n\nRegarding generalization evaluation, the absence of published benchmarks makes it hard to do a direct quantitative comparison, but Letta's agentic retrieval approach means results will vary significantly based on the underlying model and prompt engineering. Additionally, generalizability requires replication on external codebases, and current memory system evaluations typically focus on conversational tasks rather than diverse use cases.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"dff14dcc-a43a-4cb0-a9dc-2f87061abfda","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:13:53.379Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Letta memory benchmark generalization evaluation","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01GKb3pbi7wrbLXEPg64SekB","content":[{"title":"Benchmarking AI Agent Memory: Is a Filesystem All You Need? | Letta","url":"https://www.letta.com/blog/benchmarking-ai-agent-memory/"},{"title":"Feature Request: Add Standard Memory Evaluation Benchmarks (LOCOMO, MemBench, LongMemEval) · Issue #3115 · letta-ai/letta","url":"https://github.com/letta-ai/letta/issues/3115"},{"title":"Letta Leaderboard: Benchmarking LLMs on Agentic Memory | Letta","url":"https://www.letta.com/blog/letta-leaderboard"},{"title":"Letta","url":"https://www.letta.com/blog-categories/research"},{"title":"Mem0 vs Letta (MemGPT): AI Agent Memory Compared (2026)","url":"https://vectorize.io/articles/mem0-vs-letta"},{"title":"The First Controlled Benchmark of AI Memory in Coding Agents | by Markus Sandelin | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@mrsandelin/the-first-controlled-benchmark-of-ai-memory-in-coding-agents-8e0bb776d39e"},{"title":"5 AI Agent Memory Systems Compared: Mem0, Zep, Letta, Supermemory, SuperLocalMemory (2026 Benchmark Data) - DEV Community","url":"https://dev.to/varun_pratapbhardwaj_b13/5-ai-agent-memory-systems-compared-mem0-zep-letta-supermemory-superlocalmemory-2026-benchmark-59p3"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about Letta memory benchmark and generalization evaluation:\n\n## Letta Memory Benchmark Overview\n\nThe Letta Memory Benchmark (Letta Leaderboard) provides an apples-to-apples comparison evaluating different models' capabilities in terms of memory management, keeping the framework and tools constant. The Letta Leaderboard is a comprehensive benchmark suite that evaluates how effectively LLMs manage agentic memory.\n\n## Benchmark Components\n\nThe archival memory read benchmark measures how well models understand when to query for information beyond the information in their immediate context. To evaluate the agent's ability to retrieve missing information about the current topic, the benchmark stores all relevant facts in the archival memory, which is hidden from the agent unless it uses the archival memory search method, ensuring the agent has no prior knowledge and must rely on archival memory to answer correctly.\n\n## Generalization Limitations\n\nRegarding generalization evaluation, the absence of published benchmarks makes it hard to do a direct quantitative comparison, but Letta's agentic retrieval approach means results will vary significantly based on the underlying model and prompt engineering. Additionally, generalizability requires replication on external codebases, and current memory system evaluations typically focus on conversational tasks rather than diverse use cases."],"durationSeconds":7.968783791999333,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"199c7afe-8b76-47a6-a5c2-51bf7006d2a1","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"0bc33781-1dc7-4cfe-b0ac-7935a1f1b33d","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a426968626a78bc3d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NuDuAPNuKcYgU3wZEVfuCY","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"LoCoMo benchmark criticism multi-hop memory evaluation flaws\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"LoCoMo Benchmark: Long-Term Memory in Dialogues\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/locomo-benchmark-scores\"},{\"title\":\"Multiple issues with benchmark methodology and scoring · Issue #29 · MemPalace/mempalace\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace/issues/29\"},{\"title\":\"Mnemosyne: An Unsupervised, Human-Inspired Long-Term Memory Architecture for Edge-Based LLMs\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.08601\"},{\"title\":\"D-MEM: Dopamine-Gated Agentic Memory via Reward Prediction Error Routing\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.14597\"},{\"title\":\"MemR$^3$: Memory Retrieval via Reflective Reasoning for LLM Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2512.20237\"},{\"title\":\"Evaluating Long-Term Memory for Long-Context Question Answering\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2510.23730v1\"},{\"title\":\"LoCoMo Benchmark Results - Memori Labs\",\"url\":\"https://memorilabs.ai/docs/memori-cloud/benchmark/results/\"},{\"title\":\"E-mem: Multi-agent based Episodic Context Reconstruction for LLM Agent Memory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2601.21714\"},{\"title\":\"CONVOMEM BENCHMARK: WHY YOUR FIRST 150 CONVERSATIONS DON’T NEED RAG A PREPRINT\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.10523\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here are the key criticisms of the LoCoMo benchmark regarding multi-hop memory evaluation and other flaws:\n\n## Gold Standard Answer Quality Issues\n\nThe LoCoMo benchmark has limitations in terms of gold standard answers' quality and accuracy, with several imperfect and inaccurate gold standard answers provided by the benchmark. For example, the gold standard answer to \"What might John's degree be in?\" was given as \"Political science, Public administration, Public affairs,\" but in the same session where the cited evidence lies, John shared his certificate in Graphic Design.\n\n## Dataset Size and Category Reporting Flaws\n\nLoCoMo ships 1,986 QA pairs, of which 446 are category 5 (adversarial/unanswerable/often malformed), and the standard convention in published LoCoMo evaluation is to report on the 1,540 non-adversarial subset because category 5 has documented ground-truth problems. Reporting \"1,986 multi-hop questions\" without this disclosure conflates conventions and inflates the apparent dataset size.\n\n## Evaluation Protocol Issues\n\nThe LoCoMo dataset's category indexing contains latent ambiguity, with the mapping between numerical IDs and semantic categories (e.g., Multi-hop vs. Single-hop) implying a non-trivial alignment challenge, and this ambiguity has led to category misalignment in several recent studies.\n\n## Broader Methodological Flaws\n\nBenchmarks like LoCoMo exhibit consistent methodological flaws, with sample sizes per category often falling below 100 questions, making statistical comparisons unreliable, and synthetic data generation introducing detectable patterns that models exploit rather than demonstrating genuine memory. Critically, simple filesystem operations achieved 74% accuracy on LoCoMo, matching or exceeding sophisticated memory systems, suggesting the benchmark fails to meaningfully differentiate between trivial and intelligent memory approaches.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"68c64024-3302-410a-ac2f-69d7935def50","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:13:53.525Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"LoCoMo benchmark criticism multi-hop memory evaluation flaws","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01CPnmj7EKWuG6KLatgYzu2V","content":[{"title":"LoCoMo Benchmark: Long-Term Memory in Dialogues","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/locomo-benchmark-scores"},{"title":"Multiple issues with benchmark methodology and scoring · Issue #29 · MemPalace/mempalace","url":"https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace/issues/29"},{"title":"Mnemosyne: An Unsupervised, Human-Inspired Long-Term Memory Architecture for Edge-Based LLMs","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.08601"},{"title":"D-MEM: Dopamine-Gated Agentic Memory via Reward Prediction Error Routing","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.14597"},{"title":"MemR$^3$: Memory Retrieval via Reflective Reasoning for LLM Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2512.20237"},{"title":"Evaluating Long-Term Memory for Long-Context Question Answering","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2510.23730v1"},{"title":"LoCoMo Benchmark Results - Memori Labs","url":"https://memorilabs.ai/docs/memori-cloud/benchmark/results/"},{"title":"E-mem: Multi-agent based Episodic Context Reconstruction for LLM Agent Memory","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2601.21714"},{"title":"CONVOMEM BENCHMARK: WHY YOUR FIRST 150 CONVERSATIONS DON’T NEED RAG A PREPRINT","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.10523"}]},"Based on the search results, here are the key criticisms of the LoCoMo benchmark regarding multi-hop memory evaluation and other flaws:\n\n## Gold Standard Answer Quality Issues\n\nThe LoCoMo benchmark has limitations in terms of gold standard answers' quality and accuracy, with several imperfect and inaccurate gold standard answers provided by the benchmark. For example, the gold standard answer to \"What might John's degree be in?\" was given as \"Political science, Public administration, Public affairs,\" but in the same session where the cited evidence lies, John shared his certificate in Graphic Design.\n\n## Dataset Size and Category Reporting Flaws\n\nLoCoMo ships 1,986 QA pairs, of which 446 are category 5 (adversarial/unanswerable/often malformed), and the standard convention in published LoCoMo evaluation is to report on the 1,540 non-adversarial subset because category 5 has documented ground-truth problems. Reporting \"1,986 multi-hop questions\" without this disclosure conflates conventions and inflates the apparent dataset size.\n\n## Evaluation Protocol Issues\n\nThe LoCoMo dataset's category indexing contains latent ambiguity, with the mapping between numerical IDs and semantic categories (e.g., Multi-hop vs. Single-hop) implying a non-trivial alignment challenge, and this ambiguity has led to category misalignment in several recent studies.\n\n## Broader Methodological Flaws\n\nBenchmarks like LoCoMo exhibit consistent methodological flaws, with sample sizes per category often falling below 100 questions, making statistical comparisons unreliable, and synthetic data generation introducing detectable patterns that models exploit rather than demonstrating genuine memory. Critically, simple filesystem operations achieved 74% accuracy on LoCoMo, matching or exceeding sophisticated memory systems, suggesting the benchmark fails to meaningfully differentiate between trivial and intelligent memory approaches."],"durationSeconds":9.53447770799976,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"0bc33781-1dc7-4cfe-b0ac-7935a1f1b33d","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"9702cee6-a645-40b3-8b7e-c52d053fabc3","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a426968626a78bc3d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015eFuSh39bEwsUx9nELXWn5","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Mem0 benchmark methodology LOCOMO answer lookup criticism\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Multiple issues with benchmark methodology and scoring · Issue #29 · MemPalace/mempalace\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace/issues/29\"},{\"title\":\"Mem0: Building Production-Ready AI Agents with Scalable Long-Term Memory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2504.19413v1\"},{\"title\":\"Mem0: Building Production-Ready AI Agents with Scalable Long-Term Memory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.19413\"},{\"title\":\"Revisiting Zep’s 84% LoCoMo Claim: Corrected Evaluation & 58.44% Accuracy · Issue #5 · getzep/zep-papers\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/getzep/zep-papers/issues/5\"},{\"title\":\"GitHub - mem0ai/memory-benchmarks: Open-source evaluation suite for memory-augmented LLM systems · GitHub\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/mem0ai/memory-benchmarks\"},{\"title\":\"Memory Evaluation - Mem0\",\"url\":\"https://docs.mem0.ai/core-concepts/memory-evaluation\"},{\"title\":\"5 AI Agent Memory Systems Compared: Mem0, Zep, Letta, Supermemory, SuperLocalMemory (2026 Benchmark Data) - DEV Community\",\"url\":\"https://dev.to/varun_pratapbhardwaj_b13/5-ai-agent-memory-systems-compared-mem0-zep-letta-supermemory-superlocalmemory-2026-benchmark-59p3\"},{\"title\":\"State of AI Agent Memory 2026: Benchmarks, Architectures & Production Gaps\",\"url\":\"https://mem0.ai/blog/state-of-ai-agent-memory-2026\"}]\n\nI found relevant information about the Mem0 benchmark methodology and criticisms related to the LOCOMO dataset and answer lookup. Here's what the search revealed:\n\n## Benchmark Methodology Issues\n\nA key criticism is that Mem0's 92.9% score is retrieval-based (measuring whether retrieved context enables correct answers), while Mem0's published ConvoMem numbers are end-to-end QA accuracy, making the \"more than 2× Mem0\" claim a comparison of two different metrics on the same dataset.\n\nA like-for-like comparison would require either running Mem0 through the same retrieval-recall harness or running the system through end-to-end QA with the same judge.\n\n## LOCOMO Dataset Categorization Issues\n\nLoCoMo ships 1,986 QA pairs, with 446 from category 5 (adversarial/unanswerable/often malformed), and the standard published evaluation convention is to report on the 1,540 non-adversarial subset both because category 5 has documented ground-truth problems and because that category tests refusal, not memory recall.\n\nReporting \"1,986 multi-hop questions\" without disclosure conflates conventions and inflates the apparent dataset size.\n\n## Related Evaluation Disputes\n\nA critical methodological oversight identified in other evaluations was that calculations included all questions, including those from the explicitly excluded adversarial category, with corrections restricting accuracy calculations to the first four validated LoCoMo categories.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"048da27c-047a-4887-814c-ddd54f36ab5b","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:13:54.513Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Mem0 benchmark methodology LOCOMO answer lookup criticism","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01XdiqBc8LMnpgZvQBbhANAF","content":[{"title":"Multiple issues with benchmark methodology and scoring · Issue #29 · MemPalace/mempalace","url":"https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace/issues/29"},{"title":"Mem0: Building Production-Ready AI Agents with Scalable Long-Term Memory","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2504.19413v1"},{"title":"Mem0: Building Production-Ready AI Agents with Scalable Long-Term Memory","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.19413"},{"title":"Revisiting Zep’s 84% LoCoMo Claim: Corrected Evaluation & 58.44% Accuracy · Issue #5 · getzep/zep-papers","url":"https://github.com/getzep/zep-papers/issues/5"},{"title":"GitHub - mem0ai/memory-benchmarks: Open-source evaluation suite for memory-augmented LLM systems · GitHub","url":"https://github.com/mem0ai/memory-benchmarks"},{"title":"Memory Evaluation - Mem0","url":"https://docs.mem0.ai/core-concepts/memory-evaluation"},{"title":"5 AI Agent Memory Systems Compared: Mem0, Zep, Letta, Supermemory, SuperLocalMemory (2026 Benchmark Data) - DEV Community","url":"https://dev.to/varun_pratapbhardwaj_b13/5-ai-agent-memory-systems-compared-mem0-zep-letta-supermemory-superlocalmemory-2026-benchmark-59p3"},{"title":"State of AI Agent Memory 2026: Benchmarks, Architectures & Production Gaps","url":"https://mem0.ai/blog/state-of-ai-agent-memory-2026"}]},"I found relevant information about the Mem0 benchmark methodology and criticisms related to the LOCOMO dataset and answer lookup. Here's what the search revealed:\n\n## Benchmark Methodology Issues\n\nA key criticism is that Mem0's 92.9% score is retrieval-based (measuring whether retrieved context enables correct answers), while Mem0's published ConvoMem numbers are end-to-end QA accuracy, making the \"more than 2× Mem0\" claim a comparison of two different metrics on the same dataset.\n\nA like-for-like comparison would require either running Mem0 through the same retrieval-recall harness or running the system through end-to-end QA with the same judge.\n\n## LOCOMO Dataset Categorization Issues\n\nLoCoMo ships 1,986 QA pairs, with 446 from category 5 (adversarial/unanswerable/often malformed), and the standard published evaluation convention is to report on the 1,540 non-adversarial subset both because category 5 has documented ground-truth problems and because that category tests refusal, not memory recall.\n\nReporting \"1,986 multi-hop questions\" without disclosure conflates conventions and inflates the apparent dataset size.\n\n## Related Evaluation Disputes\n\nA critical methodological oversight identified in other evaluations was that calculations included all questions, including those from the explicitly excluded adversarial category, with corrections restricting accuracy calculations to the first four validated LoCoMo categories."],"durationSeconds":9.510272249999456,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"9702cee6-a645-40b3-8b7e-c52d053fabc3","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
