{"parentUuid":"1244c210-a2ca-4565-8abf-ce8bd7525d31","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a426968626a78bc3d","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_019iBhNAp6tANcyFuKZLQuAm","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01HPqnneaujQUk5yQab6E8as","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://www.letta.com/blog/benchmarking-ai-agent-memory/","prompt":"Extract concrete claims about how memory benchmarks (LoCoMo, LongMemEval) fail to measure real memory, where a filesystem baseline matches sophisticated systems, answer leakage / recall vs reasoning critiques, and any corpus-design rules they propose. Include exact numbers."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1104,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4990,"cache_read_input_tokens":12304,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4990,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqK8HuLidptvY5pfxyr","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"8c64f5b0-d2be-45dc-963a-ec7e388b35a2","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:00.001Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"8c64f5b0-d2be-45dc-963a-ec7e388b35a2","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a426968626a78bc3d","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_019iBhNAp6tANcyFuKZLQuAm","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01CXzKdCYs94NSGBYfzSi7Tx","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace/issues/29","prompt":"Extract concrete, falsifiable claims about LoCoMo benchmark methodology flaws: gold answer errors, category 5 adversarial subset, single-hop vs multi-hop misalignment, recall vs reasoning, metric conflation (retrieval recall vs end-to-end QA). Include exact numbers and category names."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1104,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4990,"cache_read_input_tokens":12304,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4990,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcFqK8HuLidptvY5pfxyr","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"faf8f4df-9ea2-4b66-b6b9-ef9eeef44cc3","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:02.211Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"31ab7337-ccc4-4fd7-977f-ee190fb3ce5c","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a426968626a78bc3d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01So3RibBc4JUw3eVqN8kuhv","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"memory benchmark answer leakage contamination filesystem all you need\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"LeakGuard: Detecting Memory Leaks Accurately and Scalably\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2504.04422v1\"},{\"title\":\"When Benchmarks Lie: Why Contamination Breaks LLM Evaluation | by Anna Alexandra Grigoryan | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://thegrigorian.medium.com/when-benchmarks-lie-why-contamination-breaks-llm-evaluation-1fa335706f32\"},{\"title\":\"Silicon Bureaucracy and AI Test-Oriented Education: Contamination Sensitivity and Score Confidence in LLM Benchmarks\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.21636\"},{\"title\":\"FictionalQA: A Dataset for Studying Memorization and Knowledge Acquisition\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.05639\"},{\"title\":\"ReplicationBench: Can AI Agents Replicate Astrophysics Research Papers?\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.24591\"},{\"title\":\"MemLens: Uncovering Memorization in LLMs with Activation Trajectories\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.20909\"},{\"title\":\"Train Once, Answer All: Many Pretraining Experiments for the Cost of One\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.23383\"},{\"title\":\"How to Find Memory Leaks in Your Application - FusionReactor Observability & APM\",\"url\":\"https://fusion-reactor.com/blog/evangelism/how-to-find-memory-leaks-in-your-application/\"},{\"title\":\"When Benchmarks Leak: Inference-Time Decontamination for LLMs\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2601.19334\"},{\"title\":\"Infini-gram mini: Exact n-gram Search at the Internet Scale with FM-Index\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.12229\"}]\n\nBased on the web search results, here's what I found about memory benchmark answer leakage and contamination:\n\n## Benchmark Contamination Overview\n\nBenchmark contamination refers to the leaking of samples from a test set into a training process in such a way that it causes inflated performance, thereby limiting the validity of the benchmark results.\n\n## Types and Forms of Contamination\n\nResearch on benchmark contamination has mainly discussed exact question leakage, near-duplicates, train-test overlap, and the evaluation biases that follow from them. However, the problem extends beyond simple exact matches. Even if the original benchmark questions themselves are removed, paraphrased texts that are semantically close to the originals, solution fragments, discussion records, distilled samples, or synthetic data may still remain in the training pipeline.\n\n## Impact on Model Evaluation\n\nBenchmark scores for LLMs can be inflated by relatively small amounts of benchmark contamination with either verbatim or rephrased test samples. Contaminated models may appear to \"understand\" questions they've memorized, which undermines comparisons across models and masks true generalization performance.\n\n## Sources of Contamination\n\nContamination is caused by (1) the benchmark being sourced from the Internet, (2) other benchmarks or online quizzes being sourced from the benchmark, (3) blogs and papers citing a benchmark entry as example, and (4) benchmark entries coinciding with online sources.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"33219b56-d4bd-4873-b47a-99d233a5385f","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:04.530Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"memory benchmark answer leakage contamination filesystem all you need","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01UCXfzDbotxx5oZpqn9bniy","content":[{"title":"LeakGuard: Detecting Memory Leaks Accurately and Scalably","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2504.04422v1"},{"title":"When Benchmarks Lie: Why Contamination Breaks LLM Evaluation | by Anna Alexandra Grigoryan | Medium","url":"https://thegrigorian.medium.com/when-benchmarks-lie-why-contamination-breaks-llm-evaluation-1fa335706f32"},{"title":"Silicon Bureaucracy and AI Test-Oriented Education: Contamination Sensitivity and Score Confidence in LLM Benchmarks","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.21636"},{"title":"FictionalQA: A Dataset for Studying Memorization and Knowledge Acquisition","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.05639"},{"title":"ReplicationBench: Can AI Agents Replicate Astrophysics Research Papers?","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.24591"},{"title":"MemLens: Uncovering Memorization in LLMs with Activation Trajectories","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.20909"},{"title":"Train Once, Answer All: Many Pretraining Experiments for the Cost of One","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.23383"},{"title":"How to Find Memory Leaks in Your Application - FusionReactor Observability & APM","url":"https://fusion-reactor.com/blog/evangelism/how-to-find-memory-leaks-in-your-application/"},{"title":"When Benchmarks Leak: Inference-Time Decontamination for LLMs","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2601.19334"},{"title":"Infini-gram mini: Exact n-gram Search at the Internet Scale with FM-Index","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.12229"}]},"Based on the web search results, here's what I found about memory benchmark answer leakage and contamination:\n\n## Benchmark Contamination Overview\n\nBenchmark contamination refers to the leaking of samples from a test set into a training process in such a way that it causes inflated performance, thereby limiting the validity of the benchmark results.\n\n## Types and Forms of Contamination\n\nResearch on benchmark contamination has mainly discussed exact question leakage, near-duplicates, train-test overlap, and the evaluation biases that follow from them. However, the problem extends beyond simple exact matches. Even if the original benchmark questions themselves are removed, paraphrased texts that are semantically close to the originals, solution fragments, discussion records, distilled samples, or synthetic data may still remain in the training pipeline.\n\n## Impact on Model Evaluation\n\nBenchmark scores for LLMs can be inflated by relatively small amounts of benchmark contamination with either verbatim or rephrased test samples. Contaminated models may appear to \"understand\" questions they've memorized, which undermines comparisons across models and masks true generalization performance.\n\n## Sources of Contamination\n\nContamination is caused by (1) the benchmark being sourced from the Internet, (2) other benchmarks or online quizzes being sourced from the benchmark, (3) blogs and papers citing a benchmark entry as example, and (4) benchmark entries coinciding with online sources."],"durationSeconds":6.720029416000471,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"31ab7337-ccc4-4fd7-977f-ee190fb3ce5c","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"1244c210-a2ca-4565-8abf-ce8bd7525d31","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a426968626a78bc3d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016zstnDREsi8m8kjRoKeWGD","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"agent benchmark transfer vs memorization held-out paraphrase split\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Your Agent Passed Evals. It Still Misread the Job. | by Duckweave | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@duckweave/your-agent-passed-evals-it-still-misread-the-job-6b99714f7560\"},{\"title\":\"AI Agents That Matter\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2407.01502\"},{\"title\":\"Benchmark methodology review + complementary approach from agentmemory · MemPalace/mempalace · Discussion #747\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace/discussions/747\"},{\"title\":\"What Should a Skill Remember? Quality-Cost Trade-offs in Cost-Aware Skill Rewriting for Language Model Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2606.09421\"},{\"title\":\"MemRL: Self-Evolving Agents via Runtime Reinforcement Learning on Episodic Memory\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2601.03192\"},{\"title\":\"MemoryAgentBench: LLM Memory Benchmark\",\"url\":\"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/memoryagentbench\"},{\"title\":\"SWE Atlas: Benchmarking Coding Agents Beyond Issue Resolution\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2605.08366v1\"}]\n\nI've found relevant information about agent benchmark evaluation, particularly regarding the distinction between memorization and transfer learning. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Transfer vs. Memorization in Agent Benchmarks\n\nAgents can succeed for the wrong reasons: memorized trajectories, overfit interaction patterns, shallow cue-following, or brittle heuristics that happen to align with the eval distribution. Overfitting is a serious problem for agent benchmarks, since they tend to be small — typically a few hundred samples.\n\n## The Role of Held-Out Test Sets\n\nHeld-out test sets are crucial in machine learning, yet many agent benchmarks do not include held-out test sets. If a benchmark is intended to be domain-general but doesn't contain held-out tasks, agent developers may take shortcuts that work only for the specific tasks represented in the dataset, resulting in agents that don't work well for other tasks in the domain.\n\n## Evaluation Approaches\n\nSome benchmarks use specific evaluation strategies to assess transfer learning. For example, in ALFWorld, the Transfer Learning phase specifically tests generalization to new instances within known categories, ensuring the agent learns procedural patterns rather than specific trajectories.\n\nAdditionally, researchers have developed methods to detect memorization, such as comparing passing agent solutions to gold patches using Jaccard similarity and difflib sequence-matcher ratio to measure whether solutions are regurgitated versus independently generated.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"24fb386e-ffc2-42ef-a816-bf108d4be9f8","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:05.963Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"agent benchmark transfer vs memorization held-out paraphrase split","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01GTYRA98jTGbSR6YtrGi9sq","content":[{"title":"Your Agent Passed Evals. It Still Misread the Job. | by Duckweave | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@duckweave/your-agent-passed-evals-it-still-misread-the-job-6b99714f7560"},{"title":"AI Agents That Matter","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2407.01502"},{"title":"Benchmark methodology review + complementary approach from agentmemory · MemPalace/mempalace · Discussion #747","url":"https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace/discussions/747"},{"title":"What Should a Skill Remember? Quality-Cost Trade-offs in Cost-Aware Skill Rewriting for Language Model Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2606.09421"},{"title":"MemRL: Self-Evolving Agents via Runtime Reinforcement Learning on Episodic Memory","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2601.03192"},{"title":"MemoryAgentBench: LLM Memory Benchmark","url":"https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/memoryagentbench"},{"title":"SWE Atlas: Benchmarking Coding Agents Beyond Issue Resolution","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2605.08366v1"}]},"I've found relevant information about agent benchmark evaluation, particularly regarding the distinction between memorization and transfer learning. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Transfer vs. Memorization in Agent Benchmarks\n\nAgents can succeed for the wrong reasons: memorized trajectories, overfit interaction patterns, shallow cue-following, or brittle heuristics that happen to align with the eval distribution. Overfitting is a serious problem for agent benchmarks, since they tend to be small — typically a few hundred samples.\n\n## The Role of Held-Out Test Sets\n\nHeld-out test sets are crucial in machine learning, yet many agent benchmarks do not include held-out test sets. If a benchmark is intended to be domain-general but doesn't contain held-out tasks, agent developers may take shortcuts that work only for the specific tasks represented in the dataset, resulting in agents that don't work well for other tasks in the domain.\n\n## Evaluation Approaches\n\nSome benchmarks use specific evaluation strategies to assess transfer learning. For example, in ALFWorld, the Transfer Learning phase specifically tests generalization to new instances within known categories, ensuring the agent learns procedural patterns rather than specific trajectories.\n\nAdditionally, researchers have developed methods to detect memorization, such as comparing passing agent solutions to gold patches using Jaccard similarity and difflib sequence-matcher ratio to measure whether solutions are regurgitated versus independently generated."],"durationSeconds":7.685977207999676,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"1244c210-a2ca-4565-8abf-ce8bd7525d31","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"8c64f5b0-d2be-45dc-963a-ec7e388b35a2","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a426968626a78bc3d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HPqnneaujQUk5yQab6E8as","type":"tool_result","content":"# Analysis of Memory Benchmark Critiques in Letta Research\n\n## Core Claims About Benchmark Failures\n\n**LoCoMo's Limited Scope:**\nThe article argues that benchmarks like LoCoMo focus on \"retrieval from long conversations\" rather than meaningful agent memory evaluation. They claim evaluation has \"primarily focused on retrieval benchmarks like LoCoMo, rather than agentic memory itself.\"\n\n**Filesystem Baseline Performance:**\nA Letta agent using simple filesystem tools achieved \"74.0%\" accuracy on LoCoMo with GPT-4o mini, exceeding what Mem0 reported as their \"top-performing graph variant\" at 68.5%.\n\n## Specific Critiques\n\n**Tool Complexity vs. Effectiveness:**\nThe authors assert that \"simpler tools are more likely to be in the training data of an agent and therefore more likely to be used effectively,\" suggesting specialized memory solutions may underperform due to being outside typical LLM training data rather than inherent technical limitations.\n\n**What Actually Matters:**\nThe piece contends that \"whether an agent 'remembers' something depends on whether it successfully retrieves the right information when needed\"—prioritizing agent capability over retrieval mechanism sophistication.\n\n## Proposed Alternatives\n\nRather than criticizing corpus design, they propose evaluating memory through:\n- Dynamic interaction testing (Letta Memory Benchmark)\n- Task-specific performance on long-running problems (Terminal-Bench)\n\n**Note:** The article doesn't discuss answer leakage, reasoning vs. recall tradeoffs, or detailed corpus-design critiques."}]},"uuid":"d117f338-8b72-43d8-952a-dd1e0baad3d3","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:06.976Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":30811,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Analysis of Memory Benchmark Critiques in Letta Research\n\n## Core Claims About Benchmark Failures\n\n**LoCoMo's Limited Scope:**\nThe article argues that benchmarks like LoCoMo focus on \"retrieval from long conversations\" rather than meaningful agent memory evaluation. They claim evaluation has \"primarily focused on retrieval benchmarks like LoCoMo, rather than agentic memory itself.\"\n\n**Filesystem Baseline Performance:**\nA Letta agent using simple filesystem tools achieved \"74.0%\" accuracy on LoCoMo with GPT-4o mini, exceeding what Mem0 reported as their \"top-performing graph variant\" at 68.5%.\n\n## Specific Critiques\n\n**Tool Complexity vs. Effectiveness:**\nThe authors assert that \"simpler tools are more likely to be in the training data of an agent and therefore more likely to be used effectively,\" suggesting specialized memory solutions may underperform due to being outside typical LLM training data rather than inherent technical limitations.\n\n**What Actually Matters:**\nThe piece contends that \"whether an agent 'remembers' something depends on whether it successfully retrieves the right information when needed\"—prioritizing agent capability over retrieval mechanism sophistication.\n\n## Proposed Alternatives\n\nRather than criticizing corpus design, they propose evaluating memory through:\n- Dynamic interaction testing (Letta Memory Benchmark)\n- Task-specific performance on long-running problems (Terminal-Bench)\n\n**Note:** The article doesn't discuss answer leakage, reasoning vs. recall tradeoffs, or detailed corpus-design critiques.","durationMs":6768,"url":"https://www.letta.com/blog/benchmarking-ai-agent-memory/"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"8c64f5b0-d2be-45dc-963a-ec7e388b35a2","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"faf8f4df-9ea2-4b66-b6b9-ef9eeef44cc3","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a426968626a78bc3d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CXzKdCYs94NSGBYfzSi7Tx","type":"tool_result","content":"# LoCoMo Benchmark Methodology Flaws: Concrete Claims\n\n## Ground Truth Errors\nThe audit documents \"~99 wrong, hallucinated, misattributed, or ambiguous answers in the LoCoMo ground truth\" across ten conversations. Examples include fabricated objects and speaker-attribution errors. This establishes an honest performance ceiling of approximately 93–94%, making 100% scores mathematically implausible.\n\n## Retrieval Bypass via top-k Configuration\nThe critical flaw: session counts per conversation are 19, 19, 32, 29, 29, 28, 31, 30, 25, and 30. Setting `top_k=50` \"exceeds that count\" for every conversation, retrieving the entire dataset regardless of embedding quality. The system reduces to \"dump every session into Claude Sonnet, ask Sonnet which one matches\"—the embedding retrieval step becomes irrelevant.\n\n## Actual LoCoMo Performance\nHonest benchmarks from the same repository document: 60.3% recall@10 without reranking and 88.9% recall@10 using hybrid v5 without language models. The 100% claim should not be cited.\n\n## Category 5 Dataset Inflation\nThe benchmark reports 1,986 questions but includes 446 adversarial/unanswerable category-5 items. Published LoCoMo evaluation conventions report on the 1,540 non-adversarial subset, as category 5 represents a different task (\"model should refuse\" rather than memory recall).\n\n## Metric Conflation Summary\nThe core problem: claiming end-to-end question answering performance while measuring only whether labeled session IDs appear in retrieval rankings—fundamentally different tasks producing incomparable numbers."}]},"uuid":"edab9a2a-abbb-40fb-ae29-ad706195bfc3","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:15.091Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":379944,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# LoCoMo Benchmark Methodology Flaws: Concrete Claims\n\n## Ground Truth Errors\nThe audit documents \"~99 wrong, hallucinated, misattributed, or ambiguous answers in the LoCoMo ground truth\" across ten conversations. Examples include fabricated objects and speaker-attribution errors. This establishes an honest performance ceiling of approximately 93–94%, making 100% scores mathematically implausible.\n\n## Retrieval Bypass via top-k Configuration\nThe critical flaw: session counts per conversation are 19, 19, 32, 29, 29, 28, 31, 30, 25, and 30. Setting `top_k=50` \"exceeds that count\" for every conversation, retrieving the entire dataset regardless of embedding quality. The system reduces to \"dump every session into Claude Sonnet, ask Sonnet which one matches\"—the embedding retrieval step becomes irrelevant.\n\n## Actual LoCoMo Performance\nHonest benchmarks from the same repository document: 60.3% recall@10 without reranking and 88.9% recall@10 using hybrid v5 without language models. The 100% claim should not be cited.\n\n## Category 5 Dataset Inflation\nThe benchmark reports 1,986 questions but includes 446 adversarial/unanswerable category-5 items. Published LoCoMo evaluation conventions report on the 1,540 non-adversarial subset, as category 5 represents a different task (\"model should refuse\" rather than memory recall).\n\n## Metric Conflation Summary\nThe core problem: claiming end-to-end question answering performance while measuring only whether labeled session IDs appear in retrieval rankings—fundamentally different tasks producing incomparable numbers.","durationMs":12683,"url":"https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace/issues/29"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"faf8f4df-9ea2-4b66-b6b9-ef9eeef44cc3","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
