{"parentUuid":"83fb2886-cf34-460b-87f9-685c2516d017","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a426968626a78bc3d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018De2NT1MFwExe7hXhu58VE","type":"tool_result","content":"# Claims and Design Rules on Agent Benchmarks and Test Set Construction\n\nI apologize, but the provided content appears to be a PDF file encoded in binary/compressed format that doesn't contain readable text about agent benchmarks, test set design, or the specific topics you're asking about (memorization vs. generalization, held-out test sets, benchmark construction practices).\n\nThe document shows PDF stream objects with compression filters but no accessible textual content discussing:\n- Held-out test set protocols for agent benchmarks\n- Overfitting dynamics in small benchmarks\n- Memorization versus shortcut learning\n- Train/test separation guidelines\n- Specific design rules for benchmark construction\n\n**To proceed, I would need:**\n1. A plain-text version of the source material, or\n2. Confirmation that the intended document was properly uploaded\n3. Direct access to the paper/article discussing these benchmark design principles\n\nIf you have the source material in text format or can point me to a specific paper on this topic, I'd be happy to extract the concrete claims and design rules you're requesting while respecting your formatting constraints.\n\n[Binary content (application/pdf, 1.2MB) also saved to /Users/gg/.claude/projects/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f/tool-results/webfetch-1782018864851-5lt4i6.pdf]"}]},"uuid":"1f2889da-b647-4dc8-8ec4-07d3d7c18b67","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:29.815Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":1235369,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Claims and Design Rules on Agent Benchmarks and Test Set Construction\n\nI apologize, but the provided content appears to be a PDF file encoded in binary/compressed format that doesn't contain readable text about agent benchmarks, test set design, or the specific topics you're asking about (memorization vs. generalization, held-out test sets, benchmark construction practices).\n\nThe document shows PDF stream objects with compression filters but no accessible textual content discussing:\n- Held-out test set protocols for agent benchmarks\n- Overfitting dynamics in small benchmarks\n- Memorization versus shortcut learning\n- Train/test separation guidelines\n- Specific design rules for benchmark construction\n\n**To proceed, I would need:**\n1. A plain-text version of the source material, or\n2. Confirmation that the intended document was properly uploaded\n3. Direct access to the paper/article discussing these benchmark design principles\n\nIf you have the source material in text format or can point me to a specific paper on this topic, I'd be happy to extract the concrete claims and design rules you're requesting while respecting your formatting constraints.\n\n[Binary content (application/pdf, 1.2MB) also saved to /Users/gg/.claude/projects/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f/tool-results/webfetch-1782018864851-5lt4i6.pdf]","durationMs":4972,"url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2407.01502"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"83fb2886-cf34-460b-87f9-685c2516d017","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"72a8326c-8143-4b3d-afb0-218f161cfc29","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a426968626a78bc3d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0165iyxnK2H187SWLk4gyxbz","type":"tool_result","content":"# LongMemEval's Corpus Design Rules Against Trivial Recall\n\n## Core Anti-Triviality Strategy\n\nLongMemEval employs several mechanisms to prevent answers being discoverable without engaging with the evidence trajectory:\n\n### 1. **Indirect Information Embedding**\n\nRather than stating facts explicitly, the benchmark requires systems to recognize information conveyed indirectly. For example, instead of a user stating \"I bought a new car last month,\" they ask for help with car insurance, incidentally revealing the purchase. This design ensures systems must perform genuine comprehension rather than surface-level pattern matching.\n\n### 2. **Five Task-Specific Designs**\n\n**Information Extraction (IE):** Requires recalling specific details from extensive histories, testing basic memorization across either user or assistant utterances.\n\n**Multi-Session Reasoning (MR):** Demands synthesizing information across multiple sessions with aggregation and comparison operations—preventing single-lookup answers.\n\n**Temporal Reasoning (TR):** Tests awareness of explicit time mentions and timestamp metadata, preventing time-agnostic retrieval from succeeding. The benchmark includes both metadata timestamps and colloquial temporal references, which systems must align.\n\n**Knowledge Updates (KU):** Specifically evaluates recognition of information changes over time—a user's job, preferences, or circumstances evolving across sessions.\n\n**Abstention (ABS):** Draws 30 questions from other types and converts them into \"false premise\" variants, testing whether systems correctly identify information *not* present in histories.\n\n### 3. **Multi-Session Construction Rules**\n\nMost questions require evidence from multiple sessions (up to six). Evidence statements are positioned diversely within sessions rather than clustered, forcing systems to retrieve and integrate across temporal boundaries. This prevents answers from being answerable by examining any single session in isolation.\n\n### 4. **Temporal Grounding Mechanisms**\n\nTimestamps are manually added to evidence sessions and questions for temporal reasoning items. The benchmark includes both formal timestamps and natural language time references (\"last weekend,\" \"three months ago\"), requiring systems to interpret and ground temporal language—a task that naive similarity-based retrieval cannot accomplish.\n\n### 5. **Distractor and Haystack Design**\n\nFollowing the \"needle-in-a-haystack\" approach, irrelevant sessions are sampled from two sources: (1) self-chat simulated on non-conflicting attributes and (2) publicly released ShareGPT and UltraChat data. Sessions are randomly inserted around evidence sessions with plausible timestamps. This creates two challenges: distinguishing relevant from irrelevant information and handling realistic context length (LongMemEvalS ≈115k tokens; LongMemEvalM ≈1.5M tokens across 500 sessions).\n\n### 6. **Quality Control on Evidence Placement**\n\nHuman annotators manually screen sessions to: verify evidence inclusion, distribute evidence across different conversation positions within sessions, and rephrase statements into colloquial language. This prevents systems from exploiting formatting artifacts or stereotyped language patterns.\n\n### 7. **No Oracle Performance Guarantee**\n\nEven with perfect retrieval (oracle setting), long-context LLMs achieved only 70–92% accuracy depending on model size, indicating genuine difficulty in synthesizing retrieved information rather than trivial lookup problems.\n\nLongMemEval's design ensures evaluation measures genuine memory capabilities—extraction, temporal reasoning, multi-hop synthesis, and update tracking—rather than simple surface-level retrieval."}]},"uuid":"3882b3a7-6d39-4faa-904f-1c173f22f697","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:33.652Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":448875,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# LongMemEval's Corpus Design Rules Against Trivial Recall\n\n## Core Anti-Triviality Strategy\n\nLongMemEval employs several mechanisms to prevent answers being discoverable without engaging with the evidence trajectory:\n\n### 1. **Indirect Information Embedding**\n\nRather than stating facts explicitly, the benchmark requires systems to recognize information conveyed indirectly. For example, instead of a user stating \"I bought a new car last month,\" they ask for help with car insurance, incidentally revealing the purchase. This design ensures systems must perform genuine comprehension rather than surface-level pattern matching.\n\n### 2. **Five Task-Specific Designs**\n\n**Information Extraction (IE):** Requires recalling specific details from extensive histories, testing basic memorization across either user or assistant utterances.\n\n**Multi-Session Reasoning (MR):** Demands synthesizing information across multiple sessions with aggregation and comparison operations—preventing single-lookup answers.\n\n**Temporal Reasoning (TR):** Tests awareness of explicit time mentions and timestamp metadata, preventing time-agnostic retrieval from succeeding. The benchmark includes both metadata timestamps and colloquial temporal references, which systems must align.\n\n**Knowledge Updates (KU):** Specifically evaluates recognition of information changes over time—a user's job, preferences, or circumstances evolving across sessions.\n\n**Abstention (ABS):** Draws 30 questions from other types and converts them into \"false premise\" variants, testing whether systems correctly identify information *not* present in histories.\n\n### 3. **Multi-Session Construction Rules**\n\nMost questions require evidence from multiple sessions (up to six). Evidence statements are positioned diversely within sessions rather than clustered, forcing systems to retrieve and integrate across temporal boundaries. This prevents answers from being answerable by examining any single session in isolation.\n\n### 4. **Temporal Grounding Mechanisms**\n\nTimestamps are manually added to evidence sessions and questions for temporal reasoning items. The benchmark includes both formal timestamps and natural language time references (\"last weekend,\" \"three months ago\"), requiring systems to interpret and ground temporal language—a task that naive similarity-based retrieval cannot accomplish.\n\n### 5. **Distractor and Haystack Design**\n\nFollowing the \"needle-in-a-haystack\" approach, irrelevant sessions are sampled from two sources: (1) self-chat simulated on non-conflicting attributes and (2) publicly released ShareGPT and UltraChat data. Sessions are randomly inserted around evidence sessions with plausible timestamps. This creates two challenges: distinguishing relevant from irrelevant information and handling realistic context length (LongMemEvalS ≈115k tokens; LongMemEvalM ≈1.5M tokens across 500 sessions).\n\n### 6. **Quality Control on Evidence Placement**\n\nHuman annotators manually screen sessions to: verify evidence inclusion, distribute evidence across different conversation positions within sessions, and rephrase statements into colloquial language. This prevents systems from exploiting formatting artifacts or stereotyped language patterns.\n\n### 7. **No Oracle Performance Guarantee**\n\nEven with perfect retrieval (oracle setting), long-context LLMs achieved only 70–92% accuracy depending on model size, indicating genuine difficulty in synthesizing retrieved information rather than trivial lookup problems.\n\nLongMemEval's design ensures evaluation measures genuine memory capabilities—extraction, temporal reasoning, multi-hop synthesis, and update tracking—rather than simple surface-level retrieval.","durationMs":11600,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v2"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"72a8326c-8143-4b3d-afb0-218f161cfc29","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"7a136fc2-3569-4097-83fa-e5b3a27e8588","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a426968626a78bc3d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Bc6RkVcBXgwMhyWwcQpNNm","type":"tool_result","content":"# LongMemEval-V2: Key Changes from v1\n\n## Core Improvements Over Previous Benchmarks\n\n**Memory Ability Taxonomy Expansion:**\nLongMemEval-V2 introduces five distinct memory abilities versus v1's broader focus:\n- Static state recall\n- Dynamic state tracking\n- Workflow knowledge\n- Environment gotchas\n- Premise awareness (new)\n\nThe paper critiques prior work: \"existing memory works mainly evaluate retrieval and reasoning over long documents or user chat histories\" with \"limited insight into whether memory systems can accumulate holistic, environment-specific knowledge.\"\n\n**Scale and Complexity:**\n- **Context depth**: 25M-115M tokens (v2-Small/Medium) vs. v1's 115k-1.5M token range\n- **Question count**: 451 manually curated questions\n- **Trajectories**: 100-500 per haystack tier\n- **Multimodal**: Includes screenshots alongside text\n\n## Anti-Leakage and Rigor Measures\n\n**Parametric Knowledge Filtering:**\nQuestions were filtered to ensure \"at least two out of four models answered the questions incorrectly\" when tested against Gemini-3-Pro, GPT-5.2, Grok-4.1, and Claude-Opus-4.6 without trajectory context.\n\n**Goal Sanitization:**\nRemoved explicit navigation hints from WorkArena/WorkArena++ goals to prevent \"procedure questions answerable by reading the route directly.\"\n\n**Multi-Hop Requirements:**\nAnswer trajectory labeling enforces \"required evidence hops\" for complex questions needing \"multiple independent pieces of evidence.\"\n\n## New Evaluation Formulation\n\n**Context Gathering Protocol:**\nRather than direct QA, memory systems expose Insert/Query APIs. Trajectories stream sequentially; returned context truncates to 200K tokens for downstream answering—simulating practical agent deployment.\n\n**Abstention Questions:**\nDeliberately flawed-premise questions testing whether models identify wrong assumptions rather than accepting them—a novel transfer evaluation dimension.\n\n## Critique of LoCoMo and v1\n\nThe paper notes LongMemEval-V1 emphasized \"limited dependencies within one or a few trajectories\" and indirect task-success evaluation. LoCoMo tested \"conversational memory\" but operated in \"user-user chat\" rather than environment-specific agentic contexts with 28-token-average states."}]},"uuid":"da170dd8-f36c-4f8a-a8c1-3ca6cfdd6db6","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:36.884Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":408863,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# LongMemEval-V2: Key Changes from v1\n\n## Core Improvements Over Previous Benchmarks\n\n**Memory Ability Taxonomy Expansion:**\nLongMemEval-V2 introduces five distinct memory abilities versus v1's broader focus:\n- Static state recall\n- Dynamic state tracking\n- Workflow knowledge\n- Environment gotchas\n- Premise awareness (new)\n\nThe paper critiques prior work: \"existing memory works mainly evaluate retrieval and reasoning over long documents or user chat histories\" with \"limited insight into whether memory systems can accumulate holistic, environment-specific knowledge.\"\n\n**Scale and Complexity:**\n- **Context depth**: 25M-115M tokens (v2-Small/Medium) vs. v1's 115k-1.5M token range\n- **Question count**: 451 manually curated questions\n- **Trajectories**: 100-500 per haystack tier\n- **Multimodal**: Includes screenshots alongside text\n\n## Anti-Leakage and Rigor Measures\n\n**Parametric Knowledge Filtering:**\nQuestions were filtered to ensure \"at least two out of four models answered the questions incorrectly\" when tested against Gemini-3-Pro, GPT-5.2, Grok-4.1, and Claude-Opus-4.6 without trajectory context.\n\n**Goal Sanitization:**\nRemoved explicit navigation hints from WorkArena/WorkArena++ goals to prevent \"procedure questions answerable by reading the route directly.\"\n\n**Multi-Hop Requirements:**\nAnswer trajectory labeling enforces \"required evidence hops\" for complex questions needing \"multiple independent pieces of evidence.\"\n\n## New Evaluation Formulation\n\n**Context Gathering Protocol:**\nRather than direct QA, memory systems expose Insert/Query APIs. Trajectories stream sequentially; returned context truncates to 200K tokens for downstream answering—simulating practical agent deployment.\n\n**Abstention Questions:**\nDeliberately flawed-premise questions testing whether models identify wrong assumptions rather than accepting them—a novel transfer evaluation dimension.\n\n## Critique of LoCoMo and v1\n\nThe paper notes LongMemEval-V1 emphasized \"limited dependencies within one or a few trajectories\" and indirect task-success evaluation. LoCoMo tested \"conversational memory\" but operated in \"user-user chat\" rather than environment-specific agentic contexts with 28-token-average states.","durationMs":10200,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2605.12493v1"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"7a136fc2-3569-4097-83fa-e5b3a27e8588","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
