{"parentUuid":"ab5205bb-2aab-4dca-9555-d0c2ca91d0e7","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a426968626a78bc3d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CbGiqPUMdm8yPmLHJSJxf9","type":"tool_result","content":"# Response Based on Available Content\n\nI cannot extract the specific section on held-out test sets and overfitting from the provided material, as the webpage only displays the **abstract and metadata** for arXiv paper 2407.01502.\n\n## What the Abstract Reveals\n\nThe abstract indicates the paper addresses these issues:\n\n- **Inadequate holdout sets**: \"many agent benchmarks have inadequate holdout sets, and sometimes none at all\"\n- **Overfitting concerns**: \"agents that are fragile because they take shortcuts and overfit to the benchmark\"\n- **Need for standardization**: The authors prescribe \"a principled framework for avoiding overfitting\"\n\nHowever, the specific concrete claims about domain-general versus task-specific benchmarks and the exact recommendations you're asking about are **not visible** in this webpage excerpt. Those details would be found in the full paper text, accessible via the PDF or HTML links provided on the page.\n\nTo obtain the detailed analysis with exact rules and recommendations, you would need to access the complete paper through one of the provided links."}]},"uuid":"868bd228-9f49-4264-8aa3-c48c49022b39","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:47.199Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":46882,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Response Based on Available Content\n\nI cannot extract the specific section on held-out test sets and overfitting from the provided material, as the webpage only displays the **abstract and metadata** for arXiv paper 2407.01502.\n\n## What the Abstract Reveals\n\nThe abstract indicates the paper addresses these issues:\n\n- **Inadequate holdout sets**: \"many agent benchmarks have inadequate holdout sets, and sometimes none at all\"\n- **Overfitting concerns**: \"agents that are fragile because they take shortcuts and overfit to the benchmark\"\n- **Need for standardization**: The authors prescribe \"a principled framework for avoiding overfitting\"\n\nHowever, the specific concrete claims about domain-general versus task-specific benchmarks and the exact recommendations you're asking about are **not visible** in this webpage excerpt. Those details would be found in the full paper text, accessible via the PDF or HTML links provided on the page.\n\nTo obtain the detailed analysis with exact rules and recommendations, you would need to access the complete paper through one of the provided links.","durationMs":4209,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.01502"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"ab5205bb-2aab-4dca-9555-d0c2ca91d0e7","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"b87cab94-a389-4ee3-b234-b5b22f0eb3ab","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a426968626a78bc3d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HDQZsDLspfWc4PCsnkMxCe","type":"tool_result","content":"# Mem0 LOCOMO Evaluation Methodology\n\n## Question Categories\n\nThe paper evaluates four question types from the LOCOMO benchmark:\n- **Single-hop**: Locating factual information within one dialogue turn\n- **Multi-hop**: Synthesizing information dispersed across multiple sessions\n- **Temporal**: Reasoning about event sequences and their ordering\n- **Open-domain**: Broader conceptual queries requiring contextual integration\n\nThe researchers explicitly excluded the adversarial category: \"The dataset originally included an adversarial question category, which was designed to test systems' ability to recognize unanswerable questions. However, this category was excluded from our evaluation because ground truth answers were unavailable.\"\n\n## Answer Evaluation Approach\n\nThe methodology employs **dual metrics**:\n\n1. **LLM-as-a-Judge (primary)**: Uses a separate capable LLM to assess responses across \"factual accuracy, relevance, completeness, and contextual appropriateness.\" The authors critique traditional lexical metrics, noting they fail when systems generate factually incorrect answers with high token overlap.\n\n2. **Lexical baselines** (F1 and BLEU-1): Reported but acknowledged as limited for semantic evaluation.\n\nFor robustness, they \"conducted 10 independent runs for each method on the entire dataset and report the mean scores along with ±1 standard deviation.\"\n\n## Evaluation Type\n\nThis is **end-to-end QA evaluation**, not retrieval-only assessment. Systems generate complete answers to questions about conversations averaging 26,000 tokens across ~600 dialogue turns, then those answers are judged for quality."}]},"uuid":"dc565e07-dbc4-4be7-b54e-10c4f50c0e20","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:51.265Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":351420,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Mem0 LOCOMO Evaluation Methodology\n\n## Question Categories\n\nThe paper evaluates four question types from the LOCOMO benchmark:\n- **Single-hop**: Locating factual information within one dialogue turn\n- **Multi-hop**: Synthesizing information dispersed across multiple sessions\n- **Temporal**: Reasoning about event sequences and their ordering\n- **Open-domain**: Broader conceptual queries requiring contextual integration\n\nThe researchers explicitly excluded the adversarial category: \"The dataset originally included an adversarial question category, which was designed to test systems' ability to recognize unanswerable questions. However, this category was excluded from our evaluation because ground truth answers were unavailable.\"\n\n## Answer Evaluation Approach\n\nThe methodology employs **dual metrics**:\n\n1. **LLM-as-a-Judge (primary)**: Uses a separate capable LLM to assess responses across \"factual accuracy, relevance, completeness, and contextual appropriateness.\" The authors critique traditional lexical metrics, noting they fail when systems generate factually incorrect answers with high token overlap.\n\n2. **Lexical baselines** (F1 and BLEU-1): Reported but acknowledged as limited for semantic evaluation.\n\nFor robustness, they \"conducted 10 independent runs for each method on the entire dataset and report the mean scores along with ±1 standard deviation.\"\n\n## Evaluation Type\n\nThis is **end-to-end QA evaluation**, not retrieval-only assessment. Systems generate complete answers to questions about conversations averaging 26,000 tokens across ~600 dialogue turns, then those answers are judged for quality.","durationMs":6159,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2504.19413v1"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"b87cab94-a389-4ee3-b234-b5b22f0eb3ab","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"21e17a5e-8582-4ee3-857b-e32d0fac8af6","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a426968626a78bc3d","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019X77jTitqQnJBVFDsDgUaZ","type":"tool_result","content":"# ConvoMem Benchmark: Critique and Design Principles\n\n## Critiques of Prior Benchmarks\n\n**LoCoMo and LongMemEval Limitations:**\nThe paper identifies several critical shortcomings in existing memory benchmarks. LoCoMo and LongMemEval are dismissed as too small-scale to meaningfully test conversational memory systems. These benchmarks suffer from \"answer leakage,\" where answers inadvertently appear in context, artificially inflating performance scores. Most significantly, the authors argue that \"your first 150 conversations don't need RAG\" (from the title), suggesting these smaller datasets don't adequately stress-test memory capabilities that retrieval-augmented generation systems are designed to handle.\n\n## Corpus Design Rules\n\nThe ConvoMem benchmark establishes design principles for more rigorous memory evaluation:\n- Multi-turn conversations with accumulated context\n- Explicit separation between recall tasks and reasoning/transfer tasks\n- Questions testing both direct memory retrieval and inference across conversation history\n- Careful validation to prevent answer leakage through inadvertent context exposure\n\n## Recall vs. Reasoning/Transfer Distinction\n\nThe benchmark distinguishes two evaluation modes:\n- **Recall**: Direct retrieval of facts stated in conversation history\n- **Reasoning/Transfer**: Requiring inference, synthesis, or application of conversational context to new scenarios\n\n## Contamination and Held-Out Concerns\n\nThe paper implements held-out test sets and addresses potential data contamination by ensuring evaluation questions don't appear in training corpora and preventing answer leakage through systematic corpus validation.\n\n[Binary content (application/pdf, 4.6MB) also saved to /Users/gg/.claude/projects/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f/tool-results/webfetch-1782018890485-910bor.pdf]"}]},"uuid":"834ff970-321c-4a98-b228-d8010771a3ce","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:56.683Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":4826057,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# ConvoMem Benchmark: Critique and Design Principles\n\n## Critiques of Prior Benchmarks\n\n**LoCoMo and LongMemEval Limitations:**\nThe paper identifies several critical shortcomings in existing memory benchmarks. LoCoMo and LongMemEval are dismissed as too small-scale to meaningfully test conversational memory systems. These benchmarks suffer from \"answer leakage,\" where answers inadvertently appear in context, artificially inflating performance scores. Most significantly, the authors argue that \"your first 150 conversations don't need RAG\" (from the title), suggesting these smaller datasets don't adequately stress-test memory capabilities that retrieval-augmented generation systems are designed to handle.\n\n## Corpus Design Rules\n\nThe ConvoMem benchmark establishes design principles for more rigorous memory evaluation:\n- Multi-turn conversations with accumulated context\n- Explicit separation between recall tasks and reasoning/transfer tasks\n- Questions testing both direct memory retrieval and inference across conversation history\n- Careful validation to prevent answer leakage through inadvertent context exposure\n\n## Recall vs. Reasoning/Transfer Distinction\n\nThe benchmark distinguishes two evaluation modes:\n- **Recall**: Direct retrieval of facts stated in conversation history\n- **Reasoning/Transfer**: Requiring inference, synthesis, or application of conversational context to new scenarios\n\n## Contamination and Held-Out Concerns\n\nThe paper implements held-out test sets and addresses potential data contamination by ensuring evaluation questions don't appear in training corpora and preventing answer leakage through systematic corpus validation.\n\n[Binary content (application/pdf, 4.6MB) also saved to /Users/gg/.claude/projects/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f/tool-results/webfetch-1782018890485-910bor.pdf]","durationMs":9615,"url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.10523"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"21e17a5e-8582-4ee3-857b-e32d0fac8af6","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
